<subSubSection id="421C273C9904E8346F40CA15C2B5F124" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="520613036818478D2A9CC607FAA96FE9" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD21BA16C1C15B17C8E6E711C7179EBB" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="C44926D3B52F74EE05EE5065A14830C8" authorityName="Zachvatkin" authorityYear="1929" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Edwardsiana" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Edwardsiana" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3BE01C61791AF48984BA3E9FB5701472" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Edwardsiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes 80 known species worldwide (
<bibRefCitation id="3345194DB143559D8A8FF9C97162F832" author="Dmitriev, DA" journalOrPublisher="Acta Faunistica Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" publicationUrl="http://dmitriev.speciesfile.org/" refId="B5" refString="Dmitriev, DA, 2003. 3i interactive keys and taxonomic databases. http://dmitriev.speciesfile.org/" title="3 i interactive keys and taxonomic databases." url="http://dmitriev.speciesfile.org/" year="2003">Dmitriev 2003</bibRefCitation>
), with two species having been reported from China. Here we record three more species from China and provide a key to all Chinese species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0A4DEDE94C3162BAF710294993FFB11E" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="020A031AC9BB168DC78AA0853D4F8B35" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9A18829086BA7F1A3E9C797541BB7B47" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">
Body cream with variable patches (Figs 
<figureCitation id="BD4D81D4BFC83B9A31BB1BA8EA129424" captionStart="Figures 1–20" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 20. Typhlocybini of China 1 - 5 dorsal view 6 - 10 head and thorax, dorsal view 11 - 15 lateral view 16 - 20 face 1, 6, 11, 16 Edwardsiana corylicola 2, 7, 12, 17 E. praedestina 3, 8, 13, 18 E. singularis 4, 9, 14, 19 Hiratettix distanti 5, 10, 15, 20 H. malaisei. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (1 - 5, 11 - 15); 0.5 mm (6 - 10, 16 - 20)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1082.73611.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/636231" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">1-3</figureCitation>
). Crown bluntly produced, medial length shorter than distance between eyes; coronal suture distinct. Pronotum slightly wider than head (Figs 
<figureCitation id="516DAE0741449DEFA73417418F28ABF5" captionStart="Figures 1–20" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 20. Typhlocybini of China 1 - 5 dorsal view 6 - 10 head and thorax, dorsal view 11 - 15 lateral view 16 - 20 face 1, 6, 11, 16 Edwardsiana corylicola 2, 7, 12, 17 E. praedestina 3, 8, 13, 18 E. singularis 4, 9, 14, 19 Hiratettix distanti 5, 10, 15, 20 H. malaisei. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (1 - 5, 11 - 15); 0.5 mm (6 - 10, 16 - 20)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1082.73611.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/636231" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">6-8</figureCitation>
). Forewing with apical area short, 1/4-1/3 of total length; RP and 
<normalizedToken id="9B18368422E89A6F4052D41659ED21EA" originalValue="MP’">MP'</normalizedToken>
petiolate or not. Hind wing with R and M confluent distally.
</paragraph>
